fields.engineering_tactics:
(1) FEATURE FLAG SERVICE: select one — PostHog (free 1M events, includes flags + experiments + replay), Statsig (generous free tier, mature experimentation engine), Eppo (geteppo.com, modern data-warehouse-native), ConfigCat (configcat.com, simple + cheap), LaunchDarkly (enterprise-grade, paid), Optimizely (enterprise, paid). For solo dev: PostHog or Statsig. (2) FLAG TYPES: (a) RELEASE FLAGS — gate new features for staged rollout. (b) EXPERIMENT FLAGS — A/B test variants assigned by user_id hash. (c) OPS FLAGS — kill-switches for outages. (d) PERMISSION FLAGS — entitlement-based features (premium tier). Each type has different lifecycle. (3) EVALUATION: client-side (PostHog SDK fetches flags on app launch, caches; risk: stale flags) vs server-side (every request re-evaluates; risk: latency). For onboarding flags, client-side fetched once at launch is acceptable. (4) DETERMINISTIC BUCKETING: hash(user_id + experiment_key) → bucket (0-99) → assign to variant by predefined ranges. Same user always gets same variant for given experiment. (5) EXPERIMENT DESIGN: define metric (e.g., onboarding_to_trial_started %) BEFORE running. Define MDE (minimum detectable effect, typically 5-10%). Run sample-size calculator. Pre-register hypothesis. (6) SAMPLE SIZE: PostHog/Statsig built-in calculators; rule of thumb: ~10K users per variant for 5% MDE on 25% baseline conversion at p<0.05. (7) RUNTIME: until pre-registered sample reached AND minimum 14 days (capture weekly seasonality). (8) NEVER STOP EARLY (peeking) without sequential-testing correction (Optimizely / Statsig sequential testing handles). (9) CUPED VARIANCE REDUCTION: PostHog / Statsig support — uses pre-experiment user data to reduce variance, smaller sample needed. (10) GUARDRAIL METRICS: every experiment monitors for regression in non-target metrics (D7 retention, paywall_view) — abort if guardrail breached. (11) CLEANUP: delete flags within 30 days of fully rolled-out feature — flag debt is real (LaunchDarkly recommends quarterly flag-cleanup ritual). (12) INTEGRATION WITH SDUI (item 31): experiment_variant determines which onboarding payload to fetch — server returns variant-specific config. (13) INTEGRATION WITH FSM (item 30): machine context includes experiment_variants[] array; states/transitions can branch on variant. (14) INTEGRATION WITH ANALYTICS (item 43): every event includes experiment_variants superproperty. (15) REVENUE CONNECTORS: RevenueCat ↔ PostHog/Statsig integration to feed payment events into experiment results. (16) CODE EXAMPLE (PostHog RN):
```typescript
import { PostHog } from 'posthog-react-native';

const variant = posthog.getFeatureFlag('onboarding_paywall_layout');
// variant: 'control' | 'side_by_side' | 'timeline' | undefined

posthog.capture('paywall_shown', {
  paywall_variant: variant,
  ...
});

if (variant === 'side_by_side') {
  return <PaywallSideBySide />;
} else if (variant === 'timeline') {
  return <PaywallTimeline />;
} else {
  return <PaywallDefault />;
}
```
(17) SAFE DEFAULTS: if flag service unavailable, default to control variant — never block app launch on flag fetch.
